augh, cry, and think. This beautiful book is easily accessible and enjoyable not only for Jewish readers, but for story-lovers of all backgrounds.Authors (in the order they appear in the book) include: Elie Wiesel, Varda Fiszbein, S. Y. Agnon, Gábor T. Szántó, Jasminka Domaš, Augusto Segre, Lili Berger, Peter Sichrovsky, Maciej Płaza, Entela Kasi, Norman Manea, Luize Valente, Eliya Karmona, Birte Kont, Michel Fais, Irena Dousková, Mario Levi, and Isaac Babel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aShort stories, JewishvTranslations into English. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aJewish literature, fiction, diaspora, anthology, translations, Elie Wiesel, Isaac Babel, Lili Berger.1 aAgnon, Shmuel Yosef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBabel, Isaac, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Lily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDomaš, Jasminka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDousková, Irena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFais, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiszbein, Varda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGold, Nora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGold, Nora, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKarmona, Eliya Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKasi, Entela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKont, Birte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Mario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator